how to modify this filter so that it makes sure the user is authenticated when going to the other pages

To modify the filter to ensure that the user is authenticated before allowing access to other pages, you can follow these steps:

1. First, create a list of pages that do not require authentication. You can use a List or a Set to store these page URLs. You can update this list in the filter `init()` method. For example:

```java
private Set<String> allowedPages;

public void init(FilterConfig config) throws ServletException {
    allowedPages = new HashSet<String>();
    allowedPages.add("/Login.jsp");
    allowedPages.add("/Register.jsp");
    // add more pages if needed
}
```

2. In the `doFilter` method, check if the requested page is in the list of allowed pages. If the page is in the list, you can allow access even if the user is not authenticated by calling `chain.doFilter(request, response);`. If the page is not in the list, then check if the session is not null and the `isLoggedIn` attribute is true.

```java
@Override
public void doFilter(ServletRequest request, ServletResponse response, FilterChain chain) throws ServletException, IOException {

    HttpServletRequest loginSessionRequest = (HttpServletRequest) request;
    HttpServletResponse loginSessionResponse = (HttpServletResponse) response;
    HttpSession loginSession = loginSessionRequest.getSession(false);

    String requestPath = loginSessionRequest.getServletPath();

    if (allowedPages.contains(requestPath)) {
        // Allow access to pages that do not require authentication
        chain.doFilter(request, response);
    } else {
        // Check if the user is authenticated
        if (loginSession != null && Boolean.TRUE.equals(loginSession.getAttribute("isLoggedIn"))) {
            chain.doFilter(request, response);
        } else {
            if (loginSession != null) {
                loginSession.setAttribute("errormsg", "Login first!");
            }
            loginSessionResponse.sendRedirect(loginSessionRequest.getContextPath() + "/Login.jsp");
        }
    }
}
```

This way, you can make sure the user is authenticated when trying to access restricted pages while allowing access to pages like `Login.jsp` and `Register.jsp` that do not require authentication.

