I apologize for the confusion. Here's the updated approach:

1. Update the `Welcome` servlet to store the user data in cookies only if the "rememberMe" option is checked in the login form.
2. In the `RegistrationServlet`, always save the user data to cookies but with a short expiration time, so that the data is available for the `Welcome` servlet to validate user credentials during login.

First, update the `RegistrationServlet`:

```java
@WebServlet("/register")
public class RegistrationServlet extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws ServletException, IOException {
        String vName = req.getParameter("username");
        String vPass = req.getParameter("password");
        String vGender = req.getParameter("gender");
        String vEmail = req.getParameter("email");
        String vPhoneNumber = req.getParameter("phone");

        // Always create cookies with short expiration
        int shortExpiry = 60; // 60 seconds
        createCookie(resp, "username", vName, shortExpiry);
        createCookie(resp, "password", vPass, shortExpiry);
        createCookie(resp, "gender", vGender, shortExpiry);
        createCookie(resp, "email", vEmail, shortExpiry);
        createCookie(resp, "phoneNum", vPhoneNumber, shortExpiry);

        resp.sendRedirect("login"); // Redirect to the login page
    }

    void createCookie(HttpServletResponse resp, String name, String value, int expiry) {
        Cookie cookie = new Cookie(name, value);
        cookie.setMaxAge(expiry);
        resp.addCookie(cookie);
    }
}
```

Now, update the `Welcome` servlet. After validating the user's credentials, store the user data in cookies if the "rememberMe" option is checked.

```java
@Override
protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws ServletException, IOException {
    String vName = req.getParameter("username");
    String vPass = req.getParameter("password");
    String rememberMe = req.getParameter("rememberMe");
    PrintWriter out = resp.getWriter();

    resp.setContentType("text/html");

    // Get saved cookies
    String savedUsername = getCookieValue(req, "username");
    String savedPassword = getCookieValue(req, "password");
    String savedGender = getCookieValue(req, "gender");
    String savedEmail = getCookieValue(req, "email");
    String savedPhoneNumber = getCookieValue(req, "phoneNum");

    // Check if login credentials match the saved cookies
    if (vName != null && vPass != null && vName.equals(savedUsername) && vPass.equals(savedPassword)) {
        // If "rememberMe" is checked, save user data to cookies with a long expiration time
        if ("on".equals(rememberMe)) {
            int longExpiry = 60 * 60 * 24; // 24 hours
            createCookie(resp, "username", vName, longExpiry);
            createCookie(resp, "password", vPass, longExpiry);
            createCookie(resp, "gender", savedGender, longExpiry);
            createCookie(resp, "email", savedEmail, longExpiry);
            createCookie(resp, "phoneNum", savedPhoneNumber, longExpiry);
        }

        printWelcome(vName, vPass, savedGender, savedEmail, savedPhoneNumber, out);
    } else {
        // Display error message and redirect to the login page or display a login form
        out.println("<h2 style='color:red'>Invalid login credentials!</h2>");
        out.println("<a href='login'>Go back to login</a>");
    }

    out.println("</body></html>");
}
```

With these changes, cookies will be created with a short expiration time during registration to store user data temporarily. When the user logs in, the `Welcome` servlet will validate the credentials and store them in cookies with a long expiration time if the "rememberMe" option is checked. The user will be able to access the `Welcome` page directly if the "rememberMe" option was checked during login.

Firstly let me provide you with a short description from the extension's GitHub description:

*How it works*
This extension works by intercepting the WebSocket frames between chrome and WhatsApp's servers using a modified WebSocket constructor (see wsHook).

Those frames are then decrypted if needed using local encryption keys, and decoded from their binary XMPP form using a javascript code from WhatsApp's original implementation.

The resulting "stanzas" are then simply checked to see if WhatsApp tries to send out a read or presence action, and if so, the extension blocks it and fakes a failure response from the server.

*Organization & Internals*
The main code of the extension is located in core/interception.js and in core/ui.js.

Other files inside the core folder deal with the infrastructure that makes the interception and the decoding works. There is also an additional parsing/ code for parsing messages (such as message_types.js) that is rarely used in the extension. background.js mainly keeps track of the saved preferences using localStorage.

If you want to see what kind of messages WhatsApp is sending and receiving over WebSocket in real-time, you can type WAdebugMode = true in the javascript console. Incoming and outgoing payloads (after decryption) will be printed out.

