This is a quiz question, the only details available are those given below. Explain the question in detail to me first, and then proceed to answer this question.
Q: The primary purpose of a Singleton is to restrict the limit of the number of object creations to only one. This oftern ensures that there is access control to resources, for example, socket or a database connection. Explain why this code is not thread safe, (i.e. more than one thread can break this code), then rewrite it so that this is thread safe:

package one;

public final class Singleton {
	private static Singleton INSTANCE = null;
	private double[] secretCode = {1.123, 2.234, 3.345};

	private Singleton() {}

	public static Singleton getInstance() {
		if(INSTANCE == null) {
			INSTANCE = new Singleton();
		}

		return INSTANCE;
	}

	//getters and setters
}

The given question presents a simplified example of the Singleton design pattern. The primary purpose of a Singleton is to restrict the number of objects of a class to only one. This is often useful for access control, for instance, when managing resources such as sockets or database connections, which should not be accessed simultaneously by multiple instances.

In this specific code snippet, the Singleton class is trying to implement the Singleton design pattern with a single instance of itself (INSTANCE). The getInstance() method is used to access the Singleton instance, and if it doesn't exist, the method creates the instance; otherwise, it returns the existing instance.

However, this code is not thread-safe because if two or more threads call the getInstance() method simultaneously, and INSTANCE is null at that time, each of them could end up creating a new Singleton object, thus, breaking the Singleton pattern. This happens because the null check for INSTANCE and instance creation are not synchronized, allowing simultaneously executing threads to potentially create multiple instances.

To make this code thread-safe, we can use the synchronized keyword in the getInstance() method body, ensuring that only one thread at a time can execute the critical section of the code. Here's the modified, thread-safe version of the Singleton class:

```java
package one;

public final class Singleton {
	private static Singleton INSTANCE = null;
	private double[] secretCode = {1.123, 2.234, 3.345};

	private Singleton() {}

	public static synchronized Singleton getInstance() {
		if (INSTANCE == null) {
			INSTANCE = new Singleton();
		}

		return INSTANCE;
	}

	//getters and setters
}
```

The keyword "synchronized" in the getInstance() method ensures that only one thread can access this method at a time. Thus, only one instance of Singleton class will be created, making the class thread-safe.

